<doc id="666177" wikidata="Q530152" url="?curid=666177" title="Picard–Lindelöf theorem">
<text>In mathematics, specifically the study of differential equations, the Picard–Lindelöf theorem gives a set of conditions under which an initial value problem has a unique solution. It is also known as Picard&#x27;s existence theorem, the Cauchy–Lipschitz theorem, or the existence and uniqueness theorem.

The theorem is named after Émile Picard, Ernst Lindelöf, Rudolf Lipschitz and Augustin-Louis Cauchy.

== Theorem ==
Let formula_1 be a closed rectangle with formula_2, the interior of formula_3. Let formula_4 be a function that is continuous in formula_5 and Lipschitz continuous in formula_6 (with Lipschitz constant independent from formula_5). Then there exists some formula_8 such that the initial value problem
formula_9
has a unique solution formula_10 on the interval formula_11.

== Proof sketch ==
A standard proof relies on transforming the differential equation into an integral equation, then applying the Banach fixed-point theorem to prove the existence of a solution, and then applying Grönwall&#x27;s lemma to prove the uniqueness of the solution.

Integrating both sides of the differential equation formula_12 shows that any solution to the differential equation must also satisfy the integral equation

:formula_13

Given the hypotheses that formula_14 is continuous in formula_5 and Lipschitz continuous in formula_6, this integral operator is a contraction and so the Banach fixed-point theorem proves that a solution can be obtained by fixed-point iteration of successive approximations. In this context, this fixed-point iteration method is known as Picard iteration.

Set
:formula_17
and
:formula_18

It follows from the Banach fixed-point theorem that the sequence of &quot;Picard iterates&quot; formula_19 is convergent and that its limit is a solution to the original initial value problem. Next, applying Grönwall&#x27;s lemma to formula_20, where formula_21 and formula_22 are any two solutions, shows that formula_23 for any two solutions, thus proving that they must be the same solution and thus proving global uniqueness of the solution on the domain formula_3 where the theorem&#x27;s hypotheses hold.

